# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: machine-tool
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:machine-tool/2-5d-machining] In machining, **2.5D** refers to a surface which is a projection of a plane into 3rd dimension – although the object is 3-dimensional, there are no overhanging elements possible.
[src:machine-tool/2-5d-machining] Objects of this type are often represented as a contour map that gives the height (*i.e.*, thickness or depth) of the object at each point.
[src:machine-tool/2-5d-machining] 2.5D objects can be machined on a 3-axis milling machine, and do not require any of the features of a higher-axis machine to produce.
[src:machine-tool/2-5d-machining] A typical example involves an XY table that positions for each hole center, where the spindle (Z-axis) then completes a fixed cycle for drilling by plunging and retracting axially.
[src:machine-tool/2-5d-machining] The code for a 2.5D machining is significantly less than 3D contour machining, and the software and hardware requirements are (traditionally) less expensive.
[src:machine-tool/2-5d-machining] **Drilling and tapping centers** are inexpensive, limited-duty machining centers that began as a 2.5-axis market category, although many late-model ones are 3-axis because the software and hardware costs have dropped with advancing technology.
[src:machine-tool/2-5d-machining] A 2.5D image is a simplified three-dimensional (x, y, z) surface representation that contains at most one depth (z) value for every point in the (x, y) plane.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining works by forcing the abrasive particles, or grains, into the surface of the workpiece so that each particle cuts away a small bit of material.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining is similar to conventional machining, such as milling or turning, because each of the abrasive particles acts like a miniature cutting tool.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] However, unlike conventional machining the grains are much smaller than a cutting tool, and the geometry and orientation of individual grains are not well defined.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] As a result, abrasive machining is less power efficient and generates more heat.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] The grain size may be different based on the machining.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] For rough grinding, coarse abrasives are used.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] For fine grinding, fine grains (abrasives) are used.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining processes can be divided into two categories based on how the grains are applied to the workpiece.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] In bonded abrasive processes, the particles are held together within a matrix, and their combined shape determines the geometry of the finished workpiece.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] For example, in grinding the particles are bonded together in a wheel.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] As the grinding wheel is fed into the part, its shape is transferred onto the workpiece.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] In loose abrasive processes, there is no structure connecting the grains.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] They may be applied without lubrication as dry powder, or they may be mixed with a lubricant to form a slurry.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Since the grains can move independently, they must be forced into the workpiece with another object like a polishing cloth or a lapping plate.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Common abrasive processes are listed below.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] The most important property of an abrasive is its hardness.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] For abrasive grains to effectively cut, they must be significantly harder than the workpiece material.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] They can be grouped based on their hardness into two categories: conventional abrasives and superabrasives.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasive materials have been used since the advent of machining.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] They are made of materials that exist naturally on Earth, and they are abundant and cheap.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasives can suitably machine most materials.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Superabrasives are much harder than conventional abrasives.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive-machining] Since they are much more expensive, they are used when conventional abrasives will not suffice.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:machine-tool/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] In its native habitat it blooms between July and December producing inflorescences that appear in groups of two to eight on an axillary raceme.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The spherical flower heads have a diameter of 5 to 10 mm (0.20 to 0.39 in) and contain 30 to 50 densely packed pale yellow to nearly white flowers.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Following flowering, smooth, firmly papery and glabrous seed pods form.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The curved, twisted or coiled pods have a biconvex shape with a length of 4 to 12 cm (1.6 to 4.7 in) and a width of 5 to 8 mm (0.20 to 0.31 in) and contain longitudinally arranged seeds.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The species was first formally described by the botanist Robert Brown in 1813 as a part of the William Aiton work *Hortus Kewensis*.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It was reclassified as *Racosperma melanoxylon* by Leslie Pedley in 1986 then returned to genus *Acacia* in 2006.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Several other synonyms are known including *Acacia arcuata*, *Mimosa melanoxylon* and *Acacia melanoxylon* var.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] In its native range, *A. melanoxylon* is found down the east coast of Australia from Queensland in the north, into New South Wales, through Victoria and west along the south coast of South Australia.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It is also found along the east coast of Tasmania.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It has become naturalised in Western Australia.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] In New South Wales it is widespread from coastal areas and into the Great Dividing Range but is not found further inland.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It is commonly found at higher altitudes in the Nandewar Range, Liverpool Range and around Orange in the west.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It is mostly found as a part of wet sclerophyll forest communities or near cooler rainforest communities.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The range of the tree extends from the Atherton Tableland in northern Queensland and follows the coast to around the Mount Lofty Range in South Australia and can grow in a wide range of podsols, especially in sandy loams.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Sapwood may range in colour from straw to grey-white with clear demarcation from the heartwood.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The heartwood is golden to dark brown with chocolate growth rings.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber is generally straight grained but may be wavy or interlocked.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Quartersawn surfaces may produce an attractive fiddleback figure.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The wood is lustrous and possesses a fine to medium texture.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The name of the wood may refer to dark stains on the hands of woodworkers, caused by the high levels of tannin in the timber.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Australian blackwood seasons easily with some possible cupping when boards are inadequately restrained.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber produces little movement once seasoned.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber is susceptible to attacked by furniture beetles, termites and powder-post beetles (sapwood) due to its physical resistance to effective preservative treatments.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber provides very high chatoyance, with an average value above 26 PZC.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] has been introduced to many countries for forestry plantings and as an ornamental tree.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It now is present in Africa, Asia, Europe, Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean, South America and the United States.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It is a declared noxious weed species in South Africa and is a pest in Portugal's Azores Islands.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It was also recently listed by the California Invasive Plant Council (Cal-IPC) as an invasive weed that may cause limited impact (Knapp 2003).
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Its use as a street tree is being phased out in some locales because of the damage it often causes to pavements and underground plumbing.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] In some regions of Tasmania, blackwood is now considered a pest.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Indigenous Australians use many parts of *A. melanoxylon* for a variety of purposes.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Seeds are harvested and consumed as a common bush tucker food, and leaves can be used as a soap or fishing poison.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The bark is either harvested to make string or prepared as a traditional analgesic, while wood is often used to make clap sticks, spear-throwers and shields.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The live plant is also employed as a fire barrier in rural settings when grown amongst other fire-resistant species.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Blackwood timber is commercially milled for wood paneling, furniture, joinery and cabinetry, tool handles, boat-building, inlaid boxes and wooden kegs.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] It is often qualitatively compared to walnut hardwood, and its physical properties are well-suited for shaping with steam.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] The bark contains a tannin content of about 20%, and is often engineered to produce decorative wood veneer.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] Plain and figured Australian blackwood is used for musical instruments; in particular, guitars, drums, Hawaiian ukuleles, violin bows and organ pipes.
[src:machine-tool/acacia-melanoxylon] More recently, blackwood has seen an increasing value as a substitute for koa wood.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] A combination of both precision and trueness, accounting for the two types of observational error (random and systematic), so that high accuracy requires both high precision and high trueness.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] This usage corresponds to ISO's definition of *accuracy* (trueness and precision).
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In the fields of science and engineering, the accuracy of a measurement system is the degree of closeness of measurements of a quantity to that quantity's true value.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] The precision of a measurement system, related to reproducibility and repeatability, is the degree to which repeated measurements under unchanged conditions show the same results.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Although the two words precision and accuracy can be synonymous in colloquial use, they are deliberately contrasted in the context of the scientific method.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] The field of statistics, where the interpretation of measurements plays a central role, prefers to use the terms *bias* and *variability* instead of accuracy and precision: bias is the amount of inaccuracy and variability is the amount of imprecision.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] A measurement system can be accurate but not precise, precise but not accurate, neither, or both.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] For example, if an experiment contains a systematic error, then increasing the sample size generally increases precision but does not improve accuracy.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] The result would be a consistent yet inaccurate string of results from the flawed experiment.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Eliminating the systematic error improves accuracy but does not change precision.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] A measurement system is considered *valid* if it is both *accurate* and *precise*.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Related terms include *bias* (non-random or directed effects caused by a factor or factors unrelated to the independent variable) and *error* (random variability).
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] The terminology is also applied to indirect measurements—that is, values obtained by a computational procedure from observed data.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In addition to accuracy and precision, measurements may also have a measurement resolution, which is the smallest change in the underlying physical quantity that produces a response in the measurement.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In numerical analysis, accuracy is also the nearness of a calculation to the true value; while precision is the resolution of the representation, typically defined by the number of decimal or binary digits.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In military terms, accuracy refers primarily to the accuracy of fire (*justesse de tir*), the precision of fire expressed by the closeness of a grouping of shots at and around the centre of the target.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] A shift in the meaning of these terms appeared with the publication of the ISO 5725 series of standards in 1994, which is also reflected in the 2008 issue of the BIPM International Vocabulary of Metrology (VIM), items 2.13 and 2.14.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] According to ISO 5725-1, the general term "accuracy" is used to describe the closeness of a measurement to the true value.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] When the term is applied to sets of measurements of the same measurand, it involves a component of random error and a component of systematic error.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In this case trueness is the closeness of the mean of a set of measurement results to the actual (true) value, that is the systematic error, and precision is the closeness of agreement among a set of results, that is the random error.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] ISO 5725-1 and VIM also avoid the use of the term "bias", previously specified in BS 5497-1, because it has different connotations outside the fields of science and engineering, as in medicine and law.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In industrial instrumentation, accuracy is the measurement tolerance, or transmission of the instrument and defines the limits of the errors made when the instrument is used in normal operating conditions.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Ideally a measurement device is both accurate and precise, with measurements all close to and tightly clustered around the true value.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] The accuracy and precision of a measurement process is usually established by repeatedly measuring some traceable reference standard.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Such standards are defined in the International System of Units (abbreviated SI from French: *Système international d'unités*) and maintained by national standards organizations such as the National Institute of Standards and Technology in the United States.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] This also applies when measurements are repeated and averaged.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In that case, the term standard error is properly applied: the precision of the average is equal to the known standard deviation of the process divided by the square root of the number of measurements averaged.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Further, the central limit theorem shows that the probability distribution of the averaged measurements will be closer to a normal distribution than that of individual measurements.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] A common convention in science and engineering is to express accuracy and/or precision implicitly by means of significant figures.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Where not explicitly stated, the margin of error is understood to be one-half the value of the last significant place.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] For instance, a recording of 843.6 m, or 843.0 m, or 800.0 m would imply a margin of 0.05 m (the last significant place is the tenths place), while a recording of 843 m would imply a margin of error of 0.5 m (the last significant digits are the units).
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] A reading of 8,000 m, with trailing zeros and no decimal point, is ambiguous; the trailing zeros may or may not be intended as significant figures.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] To avoid this ambiguity, the number could be represented in scientific notation: 8.0 × 103 m indicates that the first zero is significant (hence a margin of 50 m) while 8.000 × 103 m indicates that all three zeros are significant, giving a margin of 0.5 m.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Similarly, one can use a multiple of the basic measurement unit: 8.0 km is equivalent to 8.0 × 103 m.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] It indicates a margin of 0.05 km (50 m).
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] However, reliance on this convention can lead to false precision errors when accepting data from sources that do not obey it.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] For example, a source reporting a number like 153,753 with precision +/- 5,000 looks like it has precision +/- 0.5.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Under the convention it would have been rounded to 150,000.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Alternatively, in a scientific context, if it is desired to indicate the margin of error with more precision, one can use a notation such as 7.54398(23) × 10−10 m, meaning a range of between 7.54375 and 7.54421 × 10−10 m.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In engineering, precision is often taken as three times Standard Deviation of measurements taken, representing the range that 99.73% of measurements can occur within.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] For example, an ergonomist measuring the human body can be confident that 99.73% of their extracted measurements fall within ± 0.7 cm - if using the GRYPHON processing system - or ± 13 cm - if using unprocessed data.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In this context, the concepts of trueness and precision as defined by ISO 5725-1 are not applicable.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] One reason is that there is not a single “true value” of a quantity, but rather two possible true values for every case, while accuracy is an average across all cases and therefore takes into account both values.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] However, the term *precision* is used in this context to mean a different metric originating from the field of information retrieval (see § In information systems).
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] When computing accuracy in multiclass classification, accuracy is simply the fraction of correct classifications: ${\text{Accuracy}}={\frac {\text{correct classifications}}{\text{all classifications}}}$ This is usually expressed as a percentage.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] For example, if a classifier makes ten predictions and nine of them are correct, the accuracy is 90%.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Accuracy is sometimes also viewed as a *micro metric*, to underline that it tends to be greatly affected by the particular class prevalence in a dataset and the classifier's biases.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Furthermore, it is also called top-1 accuracy to distinguish it from top-5 accuracy, common in convolutional neural network evaluation.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] To evaluate top-5 accuracy, the classifier must provide relative likelihoods for each class.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] When these are sorted, a classification is considered correct if the correct classification falls anywhere within the top 5 predictions made by the network.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Top-5 accuracy was popularized by the ImageNet challenge.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] It is usually higher than top-1 accuracy, as any correct predictions in the 2nd through 5th positions will not improve the top-1 score, but do improve the top-5 score.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In psychometrics and psychophysics, the term *accuracy* is interchangeably used with validity and *constant error*.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] *Precision* is a synonym for reliability and *variable error*.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] The validity of a measurement instrument or psychological test is established through experiment or correlation with behavior.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Reliability is established with a variety of statistical techniques, classically through an internal consistency test like Cronbach's alpha to ensure sets of related questions have related responses, and then comparison of those related question between reference and target population.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In logic simulation, a common mistake in evaluation of accurate models is to compare a logic simulation model to a transistor circuit simulation model.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] This is a comparison of differences in precision, not accuracy.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Precision is measured with respect to detail and accuracy is measured with respect to reality.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Commonly used metrics include the notions of precision and recall.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In this context, precision is defined as the fraction of documents correctly retrieved compared to the documents retrieved (true positives divided by true positives plus false positives), using a set of ground truth relevant results selected by humans.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Recall is defined as the fraction of documents correctly retrieved compared to the relevant documents (true positives divided by true positives plus false negatives).
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Less commonly, the metric of accuracy is used, is defined as the fraction of documents correctly classified compared to the documents (true positives plus true negatives divided by true positives plus true negatives plus false positives plus false negatives).
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] None of these metrics take into account the ranking of results.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Ranking is very important for web search engines because readers seldom go past the first page of results, and there are too many documents on the web to manually classify all of them as to whether they should be included or excluded from a given search.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Adding a cutoff at a particular number of results takes ranking into account to some degree.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] The measure precision at k, for example, is a measure of precision looking only at the top ten (k=10) search results.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] More sophisticated metrics, such as discounted cumulative gain, take into account each individual ranking, and are more commonly used where this is important.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] In cognitive systems, accuracy and precision is used to characterize and measure results of a cognitive process performed by biological or artificial entities where a cognitive process is a transformation of data, information, knowledge, or wisdom to a higher-valued form.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] (DIKW Pyramid) Sometimes, a cognitive process produces exactly the intended or desired output but sometimes produces output far from the intended or desired.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] Furthermore, repetitions of a cognitive process do not always produce the same output.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] *Cognitive accuracy* (CA) is the propensity of a cognitive process to produce the intended or desired output.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] *Cognitive precision* (CP) is the propensity of a cognitive process to produce the same output.
[src:machine-tool/accuracy-and-precision] To measure augmented cognition in human/cog ensembles, where one or more humans work collaboratively with one or more cognitive systems (cogs), increases in cognitive accuracy and cognitive precision assist in measuring the degree of cognitive augmentation.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:machine-tool/additive-manufacturing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] As a Standards Development Organization, ASME continues to develop and maintains nearly 600 codes and standards in a wide range of disciplines including pressure technology, nuclear plants, elevators / escalators, construction, engineering design, and performance testing.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Machine Tool standards are developed and maintained by ASME B5 Committee, which operates under ASME's Board on Standardization and Testing.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee currently meets once a year in various locations throughout the United States.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The meeting is generally held in November and is open to the public.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The B5 Technical Committees usually meet in conjunction with the B5 Standards Committee.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Some B5 Technical Committees also meet separately in different locations throughout the year.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee and its Technical Committees are composed of experts in the field of machine tools.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Members of the B5 Standards Committee are classified in the following interest classes: Producer/Manufacturer, Regulatory, Services, General Interest, and User.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The B5 Committee works on writing new ASME American National Standards, and revising current ASME B5 and B94 standards.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee operates under procedures of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The celebration of the 100th meeting in 2022 will mark the 100th consecutive year the ASME B5 committee has met.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The following historical information marks only the beginning stages of copious collaborative work and continuous publication, review, and revision of ASME B5 Standards.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] On May 13, 1914, the ASME Committee on Meetings, Subcommittee on Machine Shop Practice began discussion on standardization of machine shop practices.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] It wasn't until September 1922 under the procedure of American Standards Association, the B5 committee was organized as a committee dedicated to machine tools.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] B5 was sponsored by the National Machine Tool Builders’ Association, the Society of Automotive Engineers, Metal Cutting Tool Institute, and The American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] On December 2, 1937, the standard for Adjustable Adapters for Multiple Spindle Drilling Heads this standard was approved by the American Standards Association and designated as American Standard (ASA B5.11-1937).
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Work on the standardization of T-slots started in 1924 and a tentative standard was published in 1927.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The first official American Standard for T-slots came in 1941.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] 11 was organized in New York on December 4, 1928, and B5 Technical Committee No.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] 4 on Spindle Noses was organized on December 5, 1928.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] These two committees worked in close cooperation with each other and with manufacturers and users of engine lathes, turret lathes and automatic lathes in developing standards for spindle noses and chucks.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] 3 on the Standardization of Machine Tapers was appointed in August, 1926, and held its organization meeting in September, 1926, in New Haven, Conn.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Three American tapers then in use, the Brown & Sharpe (1860), Morse (1862), and Jarno (1889), and the taper series adopted by William Sellers & Co.(1862) were combined into a compromise standard series which contained twenty-two (22) self-holding taper sizes.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The first edition of the Spindle Noses and Tool Shanks for Milling Machines standard, known as B5.18-1943, resulted from intensive effort dating back to 1926 by a special group of milling machine manufacturers.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] The effort to establish an American standard for Ball Screws began in July 1971 out of a need to obtain a consensus opinion relative to proposals for standardization of ball screw assemblies within the ISO/TC39 sub-committee Working Group 7.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Out of this, the subcommittee TC43 was organized with members representing manufacturers, users of ball screws, and others of general interest.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] TC43 produced ANSI B5.48, which was approved as an American National Standard and published in 1977.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Technical subcommittees under ASME B5 address the formulation and maintenance of standards in particular disciplines within the scope of the B5 charter.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Membership includes a carefully balanced representation in various interest classifications so that no one group dominates.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Some examples of the various interest classifications are: users, manufacturers, consultants, insurance interests, universities, testing laboratories, and government regulatory agencies.
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] There are over 40 Standards that are periodically reviewed to ensure they reflect new developments and technical advances (e.g., new materials, new designs and new applications).
[src:machine-tool/asme-b5] Several new standards are under development or being considered in the areas of Tool Holder Interfaces, Machine Performance Evaluation, Micromachining, Energy Assessment, and Robotics.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] A **machine tool** is a machine for handling or machining metal or other rigid materials, usually by cutting, boring, grinding, shearing, or other forms of deformations.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Machine tools employ some sort of tool that does the cutting or shaping.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] All machine tools have some means of constraining the workpiece and provide a guided movement of the parts of the machine.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Thus, the relative movement between the workpiece and the cutting tool (which is called the **toolpath**) is controlled or constrained by the machine to at least some extent, rather than being entirely "offhand" or "freehand".
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] It is a power-driven metal cutting machine which assists in managing the needed relative motion between cutting tool and the job that changes the size and shape of the job material.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The precise definition of the term *machine tool* varies among users.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] While all machine tools are "machines that help people to make things", not all factory machines are machine tools.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Today machine tools are typically powered other than by the human muscle (e.g., electrically, hydraulically, or via line shaft), used to make manufactured parts (components) in various ways that include cutting or certain other kinds of deformation.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] With their inherent precision, machine tools enabled the economical production of interchangeable parts.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] In this view of the definition, the term, arising at a time when all tools up till then had been hand tools, simply provided a label for "tools that were machines instead of hand tools".
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] This lathe "produced screw threads out of wood and employed a true compound slide rest".
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) referenced the definition of a machine tool as "any machine operating by other than hand power which employs a tool to work on metal".
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The narrowest colloquial sense of the term reserves it only for machines that perform metal cutting—in other words, the many kinds of conventional machining and grinding.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] These processes are a type of deformation that produces swarf.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] However, economists use a slightly broader sense that also includes metal deformation of other types that squeeze the metal into shape without cutting off swarf, such as rolling, stamping with dies, shearing, swaging, riveting, and others.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Thus presses are usually included in the economic definition of machine tools.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Many reports on machine tool export and import and similar economic topics use this broader definition.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The colloquial sense implying conventional metal cutting is also growing obsolete because of changing technology over the decades.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] In addition, some of the newly developed additive manufacturing processes, which are not about cutting away material but rather about adding it, are done by machines that are likely to end up labeled, in some cases, as machine tools.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] In fact, machine tool builders are already developing machines that include both subtractive and additive manufacturing in one work envelope, and retrofits of existing machines are underway.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] In modern precision engineering, the accuracy of machine tool components is often maintained through the use of a Hirth joint.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] This coupling is the industry standard for high-accuracy positioning in components such as CNC rotary tables and tool turrets.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Its straight-tooth geometry provides maximum static stiffness and positional repeatability, ensuring that the machine maintains micron-level alignment while resisting heavy cutting forces during the machining process.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Forerunners of machine tools included bow drills and potter's wheels, which had existed in ancient Egypt prior to 2500 BC, and lathes, known to have existed in multiple regions of Europe since at least 1000 to 500 BC.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] But it was not until the later Middle Ages and the Age of Enlightenment that the modern concept of a machine tool—a class of machines used as tools in the making of metal parts, and incorporating machine-guided toolpath—began to evolve.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Clockmakers of the Middle Ages and renaissance men such as Leonardo da Vinci helped expand humans' technological milieu toward the preconditions for industrial machine tools.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] During the 18th and 19th centuries, and even in many cases in the 20th, the builders of machine tools tended to be the same people who would then use them to produce the end products (manufactured goods).
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] However, from these roots also evolved an industry of machine tool builders as we define them today, meaning people who specialize in building machine tools for sale to others.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Historians of machine tools often focus on a handful of major industries that most spurred machine tool development.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Others could be included in this list as well, but they tend to be connected with the root causes already listed.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Machine tools filled a need created by textile machinery during the Industrial Revolution in England in the middle to late 1700s.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Until that time, machinery was made mostly from wood, often including gearing and shafts.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The increase in mechanization required more metal parts, which were usually made of cast iron or wrought iron.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Cast iron could be cast in molds for larger parts, such as engine cylinders and gears, but was difficult to work with a file and could not be hammered.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Red hot wrought iron could be hammered into shapes.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Room temperature wrought iron was worked with a file and chisel and could be made into gears and other complex parts; however, hand working lacked precision and was a slow and expensive process.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] James Watt was unable to have an accurately bored cylinder for his first steam engine, trying for several years until John Wilkinson invented a suitable boring machine in 1774, boring Boulton & Watt's first commercial engine in 1776.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The advance in the accuracy of machine tools can be traced to Henry Maudslay and refined by Joseph Whitworth.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The process by which the master plane gages were produced dates back to antiquity but was refined to an unprecedented degree in the Maudslay shop.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The process begins with three square plates each given an identification (ex., 1,2 and 3).
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The first step is to rub plates 1 and 2 together with a marking medium (called bluing today) revealing the high spots which would be removed by hand scraping with a steel scraper, until no irregularities were visible.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] This would not produce true plane surfaces but a "ball and socket" concave-concave and convex-convex fit, as this mechanical fit, like two perfect planes, can slide over each other and reveal no high spots.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The rubbing and marking are repeated after rotating 2 relative to 1 by 90 degrees to eliminate concave-convex "potato-chip" curvature.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Next, plate number 3 is compared and scraped to conform to plate number 1 in the same two trials.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] In this manner plates number 2 and 3 would be identical.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Next plates number 2 and 3 would be checked against each other to determine what condition existed, either both plates were "balls" or "sockets" or "chips" or a combination.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] These would then be scraped until no high spots existed and then compared to plate number 1.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Repeating this process of comparing and scraping the three plates could produce plane surfaces accurate to within millionths of an inch (the thickness of the marking medium).
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The traditional method of producing the surface gages used an abrasive powder rubbed between the plates to remove the high spots, but it was Whitworth who contributed the refinement of replacing the grinding with hand scraping.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Sometime after 1825, Whitworth went to work for Maudslay and it was there that Whitworth perfected the hand scraping of master surface plane gages.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] With the creation of master plane gages of such high accuracy, all critical components of machine tools (i.e., guiding surfaces such as machine ways) could then be compared against them and scraped to the desired accuracy.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The first machine tools offered for sale (i.e., commercially available) were constructed by Matthew Murray in England around 1800.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Others, such as Henry Maudslay, James Nasmyth, and Joseph Whitworth, soon followed the path of expanding their entrepreneurship from manufactured end products and millwright work into the realm of building machine tools for sale.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Important early machine tools included the slide rest lathe, screw-cutting lathe, turret lathe, milling machine, pattern tracing lathe, shaper, and metal planer, which were all in use before 1840.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] With these machine tools the decades-old objective of producing interchangeable parts was finally realized.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] An important early example of something now taken for granted was the standardization of screw fasteners such as nuts and bolts.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Before about the beginning of the 19th century, these were used in pairs, and even screws of the same machine were generally not interchangeable.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Methods were developed to cut screw thread to a greater precision than that of the feed screw in the lathe being used.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] This led to the bar length standards of the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] American production of machine tools was a critical factor in the Allies' victory in World War II.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Production of machine tools tripled in the United States in the war.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] No war was more industrialized than World War II, and it has been written that the war was won as much by machine shops as by machine guns.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The production of machine tools is concentrated in about 10 countries worldwide: China, Japan, Germany, Italy, South Korea, Taiwan, Switzerland, US, Austria, Spain and a few others.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Machine tool innovation continues in several public and private research centers worldwide.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Machine tools can be powered from a variety of sources.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Human and animal power (via cranks, treadles, treadmills, or treadwheels) were used in the past, as was water power (via water wheel); however, following the development of high-pressure steam engines in the mid 19th century, factories increasingly used steam power.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Factories also used hydraulic and pneumatic power.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Many small workshops continued to use water, human and animal power until electrification after 1900.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Today most machine tools are powered by electricity; hydraulic and pneumatic power are sometimes used, but this is uncommon.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Machine tools can be operated manually, or under automatic control.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Early machines used flywheels to stabilize their motion and had complex systems of gears and levers to control the machine and the piece being worked on.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Soon after World War II, the numerical control (NC) machine was developed.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] NC machines used a series of numbers punched on paper tape or punched cards to control their motion.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] In the 1960s, computers were added to give even more flexibility to the process.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Such machines became known as computerized numerical control (CNC) machines.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] NC and CNC machines could precisely repeat sequences over and over, and could produce much more complex pieces than even the most skilled tool operators.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Before long, the machines could automatically change the specific cutting and shaping tools that were being used.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] For example, a drill machine might contain a magazine with a variety of drill bits for producing holes of various sizes.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Previously, either machine operators would usually have to manually change the bit or move the work piece to another station to perform these different operations.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The next logical step was to combine several different machine tools together, all under computer control.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] These are known as machining centers, and have dramatically changed the way parts are made.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] When fabricating or shaping parts, several techniques are used to remove unwanted metal.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Other techniques are used to *add* desired material.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] Devices that fabricate components by selective *addition* of material are called rapid prototyping machines.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The worldwide market for machine tools was approximately $81 billion in production in 2014 according to a survey by market research firm Gardner Research.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] The largest producer of machine tools was China with $23.8 billion of production followed by Germany and Japan at neck and neck with $12.9 billion and $12.88 billion respectively.
[src:machine-tool/machine-tool] South Korea and Italy rounded out the top 5 producers with revenue of $5.6 billion and $5 billion respectively.
